english:
  title: Preface to the Poems Exchanged at the Gathering of Elders at Wonam
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: "In ancient times, when gentlemen served their lord, they fulfilled their duty completely. Thus the lord reciprocated with abundant courtesy and generosity. When propriety was rich and duty complete, when minds aligned and spirits merged, clouds naturally followed the dragon and fish naturally swam in water. Even in their declining years, these men continued in cycles of rest and service, enjoying leisure and ease with silver hair and white beards, yet never forgetting the nation even for a day away from office. When counsel was needed, they decided. When difficulty arose, they responded. How deep was the mutual understanding between lord and minister!\n\nI have thrice marveled at the poems composed by these elders gathered at Wonam. When the royal court journeyed south, seven ministers accompanied the king—the Marquis of Ququ, the Marquis of Cheolseong, the Marquis of Chilwon, the Marquis of Hoisan, the Marquis of Dangseong, the Lord of Suchun, and the Lord of Gyeseong. The king greatly favored them and treated them with the utmost courtesy. In the eighth month, the entourage paused at Wonam. The following day they traveled to Sorni Temple, but heavy rain drove them back to Wonam, where they remained another day.\n\nThese elders, content in their retirement yet eager for the journey home, raised cups and toasted one another, accompanied by music. General Kim Ha-chuk played the flute, and General Kim Sa-hyuk plucked the zither. With gray faces and white hair, they laughed and exchanged words, appearing like immortals themselves. Yet who would have believed that so recently we endured such hardship, and now in peace, culture blooms so brilliantly?\n\nThough these elders are aged, they grieve that the king cannot rest within the palace, but instead bears weapons and stands watch in the field through wind and rain, heat and cold. The hundred officials follow their example, each devoted to duty, never faltering. How much their presence and influence moves the hearts of the people and strengthens the nation through their daily efforts! Are they any less than those who sit in the councils of state and issue commands? \n\nTao Yuanming of Chaisang and the Seven Sages of the Bamboo Grove were called enemies of propriety, yet men still delight in painting and singing of them. How much more fitting to commemorate this noble gathering at Wonam, which provides the vital force of the nation! Yet I wonder—who among today's artists can paint well? Who can compose music? Should one wish to join the ranks of zither and flute players as a younger participant, it is no longer possible. But as for composing verses—who but one as unworthy as myself would venture to compose the first? Observe: the peaks of Sorni Mountain stand majestic and soaring toward heaven—is this not what we younger generations should revere? The grace and literary brilliance of these elders rivals even the mountains themselves. What need then for song or paint?"
  footnotes:
    - Wonam (元巖) was a scenic location where this historical gathering took place during the royal court's southern journey.
    - The reference to Tao Yuanming (陶淵明) of Chaisang and the Seven Sages of the Bamboo Grove invokes the classical ideal of noble reclusion, which Lee Saek contrasts with the active service of the Wonam elders.
    - The 'vital force of the nation' (元氣) is a Confucian concept representing the fundamental energy and virtue that sustains the state.
